  "signature": "ed25519:9f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0a1b2c3d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022R1) must be under version control with documented verification tests and traceable release notes. All simulation scripts committed to institutional repository with issue tracking. Required for MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022R1 is used under a validated institutional license. Version control is maintained via Git repository with tagged releases. Solver verification test suite passes all benchmark cases documented in the ANSYS verification manual. SQA level 2 is met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations through comparison with analytical solutions or established benchmarks for at least two canonical flow cases relevant to rotating machinery. MRL 2 requires documented evidence of benchmark agreement within 1% for laminar cases.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed using the lid-driven cavity benchmark and the Taylor-Couette flow problem. ANSYS Fluent results agreed with analytical solutions to within 0.4% for laminar cases. Turbulent benchmark (backward-facing step) showed agreement within 3% for reattachment length, consistent with published literature. Gradation 2 is satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "A formal mesh convergence study using at least three systematically refined meshes must be completed. Grid Convergence Index (GCI) must be reported for the primary QoI (hemolysis index). GCI < 5% required at MRL 2; GCI < 2% targeted for exceeding the required level.",
      "rationale": "Three mesh resolutions were evaluated: 2.1M, 5.8M, and 14.2M elements. Richardson extrapolation yielded a GCI of 1.8% for the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) at the worst-case operating point (6 L/min, 3500 RPM). The achieved level of 3 reflects the rigorous GCI analysis exceeding the MRL 2 threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Experimental validation tests were conducted using bovine blood (hematocrit 33 ± 2%) at 37°C, matching physiological CPB conditions. Flow rates of 2, 4, 5, 6, and 8 L/min were tested at rotational speeds of 2500 and 3500 RPM, spanning the device operating envelope. Inlet and outlet pressures were monitored with calibrated transducers traceable to NIST standards. The test conditions bracket the intended COU operating range, satisfying the requirements for MRL 2. All five flow-speed combinations specified in the COU were covered, and boundary conditions imposed in the CFD model were taken directly from the experimental setup documentation."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted NIH values must agree with experimental measurements within ±25% across all tested operating points. Pressure-head predictions must agree within ±5%. Both criteria must be met simultaneously for level 2 to be declared achieved.",
      "rationale": "Predicted NIH values agreed with experimental measurements within 18% across all five operating points, and pressure-head predictions agreed within 3.2%. Both acceptance thresholds are satisfied. The relative hemolysis index RH remained below 1.0 for all comparisons against the predicate device baseline, consistent with the COU acceptance criterion."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The primary QoI (NIH / RH index) must be directly linked to the clinical endpoint (hemolysis risk) and must be computable from the CFD outputs without unvalidated post-processing transformations. The power-law hemolysis damage model constants must be sourced from peer-reviewed literature.",
      "rationale": "The normalized index of hemolysis is the established regulatory QoI for blood pump hemolysis assessment and is directly linked to clinical red blood cell damage. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model constants are drawn from peer-reviewed sources. No unvalidated transformations are applied between CFD shear stress fields and the reported NIH."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must use the same pump geometry, blood analogue properties, and operating range as the COU. Deviations in geometry or fluid properties must be documented and their impact on QoI bounded by sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "Validation experiments were conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry identical to the COU device. Bovine blood was used as specified in FDA guidance for hemolysis testing. The operating envelope tested encompasses all five COU flow-speed combinations. No geometric deviations were introduced between the validation model and the COU model."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "Solver convergence was monitored through residual tracking for all transport equations. All simulations achieved residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity and momentum equations and below 1×10⁻⁶ for the turbulence quantities. Double-precision arithmetic was employed throughout. Iterative convergence was additionally confirmed by monitoring NIH at each iteration; variation in NIH over the final 500 iterations was less than 0.3%. These results confirm that numerical solver error is negligible relative to discretization error and does not compromise the credibility of the QoI predictions. At MRL 2, only a basic demonstration of convergence is required; the achieved evidence exceeds this threshold."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 2, a documented review by a second qualified analyst of simulation setup files, boundary condition assignments, and post-processing scripts is sufficient to satisfy level 1.",
      "rationale": "A peer review of all simulation input files, boundary condition assignments, and post-processing scripts was performed by a second qualified CFD analyst. No errors in model setup were identified. The review was documented in the project quality record QR-2024-CPB-007."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The turbulence model selection must be justified by reference to published validation studies for rotating blood-contacting devices. Sensitivity to turbulence model choice must be assessed across at least two model variants. The hemolysis damage model must be identified as appropriate for the shear stress magnitudes and exposure times encountered in the pump.",
      "rationale": "The SST k-ω turbulence model was selected based on published literature demonstrating superior performance for rotating blood pump flows compared to standard k-ε. A sensitivity study comparing SST k-ω and realizable k-ε showed NIH differences of less than 8%, within acceptable bounds. The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model is appropriate for the shear stress range (10–500 Pa) and exposure times (1–10 ms) characteristic of centrifugal blood pumps."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 when model influence is Medium and input uncertainty has been bounded by the test conditions factor assessment.",
      "rationale": "At MRL 2 with medium model influence, a full uncertainty quantification of model inputs is not required. Inlet velocity profiles and rotational speed are taken directly from experimental measurements with calibrated instrumentation. Blood viscosity is assigned per FDA guidance nominal values. Input sensitivity is implicitly bounded by the test conditions assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "At MRL 2, documentation that blood samples were sourced from a qualified supplier with hematocrit and viscosity within specified ranges is sufficient.",
      "rationale": "Bovine blood was sourced from a qualified supplier (Lampire Biological Laboratories). Hematocrit was adjusted to 33 ± 2% and viscosity confirmed at 3.5 ± 0.3 cP at 37°C prior to each test run. Sample preparation followed the ASTM F1841 standard."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "rationale": "The equivalency of input parameters between the validation experiments and the COU simulation was evaluated systematically. Pump geometry was identical between validation and COU models (same STL source file, no geometric modifications). Rotational speed, flow rate, and fluid temperature matched within measurement uncertainty across all five operating points. Inlet velocity profiles in the CFD model were derived from the experimentally measured flow rates assuming fully developed turbulent profiles, consistent with the upstream tubing length in the test circuit. No dimensionless scaling was required, as the validation and COU operate at the same physical scale. The equivalency assessment confirms that the validation evidence is directly applicable to the COU without extrapolation corrections, satisfying the level 2 requirement at MRL 2."
    }
  ],
